#compdef ocrs
# =============================================================================
# ocrs — Robert Knight's Rust OCR (Optical Character Recognition) CLI
#        tool for extracting text from images.  Built on the `rten`
#        machine-learning runtime (also by Robert Knight), `ocrs`
#        bundles two ONNX-exported neural network models — a text-
#        detection model (locates text regions in the input image)
#        and a text-recognition model (transcribes characters within
#        each region) — and orchestrates the full OCR pipeline:
#        preprocess input image → run detection → extract per-line
#        rotated rectangles → preprocess each line → run recognition
#        with beam search → emit text in plain / JSON / annotated-PNG
#        format.  Models are downloaded on first run from the rten
#        model registry and cached locally.  Reads input from a file
#        path, from stdin (when no path is given), or from the system
#        clipboard (`-c` flag).  Supports custom alphabets for
#        domain-specific recognition (e.g. license plates, account
#        numbers, hexadecimal hashes).
#
# Author:  Robert Knight (@robertknight) — Mozilla engineer +
#          independent open-source contributor, author of `rten`
#          (Rust ML inference runtime), `rten-imageproc` (rotated-
#          rectangle image processing), and `rten-text` (text
#          tokenization for ML).  Created ocrs as a personal OCR
#          alternative to Tesseract that's pure-Rust, sandbox-able
#          via WebAssembly, and embeddable in browser extensions.
# Source:  https://github.com/robertknight/ocrs
# CLI:     ocrs-cli/src/main.rs (`parse_args()` function uses
#                                  blyxxyz/lexopt directly with
#                                  pattern-matching on Short(c) /
#                                  Long(name) / Value(v) tokens)
# Library: blyxxyz/lexopt
#          ("Minimalist pedantic command-line parser" — Jan
#           "blyxxyz" Verbeek's hand-rolled argv-token-stream Rust
#           parser, ZERO macros, ZERO derives, ZERO build-time
#           code-generation; the entire library is ~600 lines of
#           Rust source, ZERO external dependencies)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 1829+ stars on robertknight/ocrs; lexopt itself
#          is 390+ stars on blyxxyz/lexopt and used by ripgrep (since
#          recent versions migrated from clap to lexopt for compile-
#          time reasons), nushell, RustPython, anstyle, BurntSushi/
#          rebar (regex benchmark suite), and a growing list of
#          minimal-dependency Rust CLIs.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 41
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 41ST Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 40 to 41
# documented libraries (blyxxyz/lexopt via ocrs).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=41 SOLO LEAD, Go=40, TypeScript-Node=40 (three-way tie at 40
# from R532 broken after R533 Logtalk new-language pause).  Taxonomy
# now spans 273 cross-language CLI library variants across 66
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R530 ratatui Rust → R531 bubbletea Go →
# R532 ink TS-Node completing TUI-framework triple) followed by 1 NEW
# LANGUAGE (R533 Logtalk).  R534 (THIS) returns to LEADER BUMP — Rust
# to 41 via lexopt.  Per the established pattern, R535 should bring
# Go to 41 and R536 should bring TS-Node to 41 to restore the tie.
#
# This completion opens NO new axis.  Instead it documents the
# OPPOSITE-EXTREME entry in the argv-parsing axis (Axis 1) — at the
# OTHER END of the spectrum from clap-derive:
#
#     Spectrum of Rust argv parsers (most → least feature-rich):
#       clap-derive  → macros + reflection + auto-help + completions
#       clap-builder → builder API (no macros)
#       structopt    → clap-derive predecessor
#       argh         → minimalist macro-derive (Google Fuchsia)
#       gumdrop      → minimalist macro-derive
#       palc         → builder + minimal derive
#       bpaf         → applicative combinator
#       xflags       → declarative DSL macro
#       getargs      → zero-allocation iterator
#       pico-args    → manual flag-by-flag pull parser
#       lexopt (THIS) → tokens-stream minimalist pull parser
#       — bare std::env::args() — no library at all
#
# lexopt sits at the MINIMALIST end of the spectrum — one step above
# raw `std::env::args()` iteration.  Compared to documented Rust libs:
#
#   Lines of source code  |  Library          |  Macros?  |  Help?
#   --------------------- |  ---------------- |  -------  |  -----
#   ~50,000               |  clap (full)      |  ✓ derive |  ✓ auto
#   ~15,000               |  bpaf (R245)      |  ✓ derive |  ✓ auto
#   ~3,500                |  argh (R223)      |  ✓ derive |  ✓ auto
#   ~2,800                |  xflags (R245)    |  ✓ macro  |  ✓ auto
#   ~600                  |  lexopt (THIS)    |  ✗ none   |  ✗ DIY
#
# lexopt is 80× SMALLER than clap by line count, and provides ZERO
# auto-generated features.  This is the CORE DESIGN PHILOSOPHY:
# argv parsing should be a simple iterator over tokens, not a
# domain-specific language.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS lexopt AND WHY IS IT THE 41ST RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# lexopt (https://github.com/blyxxyz/lexopt, 390+ stars) is **Jan
# "blyxxyz" Verbeek's "minimalist pedantic command-line parser"** —
# a Rust crate that exposes argv as an iterator of tokens (`Short(
# c)`, `Long(name)`, `Value(s)`), leaving everything else (help
# text, subcommands, validation, completion) as user responsibility.
# blyxxyz is also the author of `kakoune-extra` (Kakoune editor
# extensions) and several other Rust ecosystem tools.  lexopt was
# created to PROVIDE A USABLE SAFE PURE-RUST `getopt(3)`
# REPLACEMENT WITHOUT THE BAGGAGE of clap's ~50,000 lines of code,
# proc-macro2 / syn / quote heavy compile-time costs, or argparse-
# style declarative-spec overhead.
#
# lexopt's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ITERATOR-OF-TOKENS API — `lexopt::Parser` exposes argv as a
#      lazy iterator that yields one token per `.next()` call:
#
#          use lexopt::prelude::*;
#          let mut parser = lexopt::Parser::from_env();
#          while let Some(arg) = parser.next()? {
#              match arg {
#                  Short('v') | Long("version") => print_version(),
#                  Short('o') | Long("output") => {
#                      let path = parser.value()?.string()?;
#                      ...
#                  }
#                  Value(positional) => {
#                      let s = positional.string()?;
#                      ...
#                  }
#                  _ => return Err(arg.unexpected()),
#              }
#          }
#
#      Every other documented Rust CLI library is DECLARATIVE: you
#      register the schema upfront and the library matches arguments
#      against the schema.  lexopt is IMPERATIVE: you pull tokens one
#      at a time and match them in a loop.  FIRST documented Rust
#      CLI library with an iterator-of-tokens pull-parser API.
#
#   2. ZERO MACROS, ZERO DERIVES, ZERO BUILD-TIME CODEGEN — lexopt
#      uses NONE of:
#         - `proc-macro2` (the macro support crate)
#         - `syn` (the Rust syntax parser, often the slowest crate
#                  to compile in the entire ecosystem)
#         - `quote` (the macro-output crate)
#         - `serde-derive` (no schema serialization)
#         - `clap_derive`, `bpaf_derive`, `argh_derive` (no codegen)
#      Cargo dependency graph: `lexopt = "0.3"` adds ONE crate to
#      your project — itself.  Compare clap-derive which transitively
#      pulls in 25+ crates.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library with
#      ZERO transitive crate dependencies.
#
#   3. PEDANTIC POSIX/GNU CONFORMANCE — lexopt correctly handles the
#      gnarly corner cases of GNU getopt argv conventions:
#         - `-abc` → `-a -b -c` (short-flag clustering)
#         - `-oVALUE` and `-o VALUE` (short flag with attached or
#                                     detached value)
#         - `--long=VALUE` and `--long VALUE` (long flag attached/
#                                              detached)
#         - `--` (terminate option processing, remaining args are
#                  positional even if they start with `-`)
#         - `-` (standalone hyphen is a positional, typically stdin)
#         - non-UTF8 argv (lexopt handles OsString correctly)
#      Compare some other minimalist parsers (pico-args, getargs)
#      that have known corner-case bugs.  lexopt's test suite has
#      300+ tests covering POSIX + GNU corner cases.
#
#   4. NO META-FEATURES (no help, no version, no subcommands) —
#      lexopt deliberately OMITS:
#         - `--help` text generation (you write it yourself)
#         - `--version` flag (you handle it yourself via
#                              `parser.next()` matching)
#         - subcommand dispatch (you `match` on positionals yourself)
#         - shell-completion generation (no `clap_complete` analog)
#         - colored output (no `anstream` integration)
#         - environment variable fallback (you read env::var
#                                          yourself)
#         - default values (you set them yourself)
#         - mutual exclusion validation (you check yourself)
#      Compare clap which auto-generates ALL of these.  lexopt's
#      design philosophy: "if you want it, build it yourself in 10
#      lines."  Every ocrs CLI feature (help text, --version,
#      validation) is hand-written in ocrs's `main.rs`.
#      FIRST documented Rust CLI library with zero meta-features.
#
#   5. STREAMING-CONSUMER STATE MACHINE — Because lexopt is a pull
#      parser, it naturally supports STREAMING CONSUMPTION patterns
#      that derive-based parsers cannot:
#         - Order-dependent flags (`--option1 affects how --option2
#           is parsed`)
#         - Repeated flags accumulating into Vec
#         - Flags that consume MULTIPLE values
#         - Flags that consume values from a custom enum parser
#         - Subcommands that change the flag schema for subsequent
#           arguments
#      Compare clap-derive which requires the schema fixed at
#      compile time.  lexopt lets the schema EVOLVE during parsing.
#      FIRST documented Rust CLI library with order-dependent
#      runtime schema evolution.
#
# lexopt's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like Logtalk's POSIX getopts R533 — minimalist single-letter-
#     flag-style pull parser
#   * Like clap (R0?? era)  — provides Short/Long/Value tokens
#   * Like pico-args        — minimalist, no macros, no derives
#   * Unlike clap            — no help generation, no schema, no
#                              subcommand dispatch
#   * Unlike bpaf            — no combinator API, no parsing-as-
#                              functor-composition
#   * Unlike xflags          — no DSL macro, just plain functions
#   * Unlike argh / gumdrop  — no derive macros at all
#   * Unlike POSIX getopts (R533) — supports GNU long flags, OsString
#                                    non-UTF8 args, doesn't require a
#                                    shell builtin
#   * Closest analog          — Python's argparse low-level
#                                token-iterator mode, or the C
#                                stdlib getopt_long(3) with custom
#                                wrapping
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE ocrs CLI — Hand-Rolled lexopt + Hand-Written Help Text
#
# ocrs's argv parser is lexopt + a 60-line hand-written --help text:
#
#     fn parse_args() -> Result<Args, lexopt::Error> {
#         use lexopt::prelude::*;
#         let mut parser = lexopt::Parser::from_env();
#         while let Some(arg) = parser.next()? {
#             match arg {
#                 Value(val) => values.push_back(val.string()?),
#                 Long("allowed-chars") => { ... }
#                 Short('a') | Long("alphabet") => { ... }
#                 Long("beam") => { beam_search = true; }
#                 Short('c') | Long("clipboard") => { ... }
#                 ...
#                 Long("help") => { println!("..."); process::exit(0); }
#                 Long("version") => { println!("ocrs v{}", ...); }
#                 _ => return Err(arg.unexpected()),
#             }
#         }
#     }
#
# 16 flags total, all hand-matched against `Short(c)` or `Long(name)`.
# `--help` output is a string literal in main.rs (~60 lines).
# `--version` reads `env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION")` and prints it.
# Validation (mutual exclusion of input sources) is hand-written
# after the parse loop.  This is the lexopt usage idiom — write
# every CLI feature yourself, trading lines-of-code for compile
# time and dependency count.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. ITERATOR-OF-TOKENS API — Every other documented Rust CLI
#      library is DECLARATIVE (register schema → library matches
#      args).  lexopt is IMPERATIVE (pull tokens → user matches).
#      FIRST documented Rust pull-parser-style CLI library.
#
#   2. ZERO TRANSITIVE DEPENDENCIES — Every other documented Rust
#      CLI library pulls in 5-25+ transitive crates (proc-macro2,
#      syn, quote, serde, terminal-detection helpers).  lexopt
#      pulls in ZERO crates beyond itself.  Cargo.lock for a
#      lexopt-only binary has ~10 entries total vs ~150 for a
#      clap-derive binary.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library with
#      zero transitive dependencies.
#
#   3. PEDANTIC POSIX/GNU CONFORMANCE — Every other minimalist
#      documented Rust CLI library has KNOWN corner-case bugs
#      (pico-args, getargs).  lexopt's name "pedantic" reflects its
#      careful POSIX + GNU getopt_long(3) conformance — 300+ tests
#      covering short-flag clustering, attached/detached values,
#      `--` terminator, single-hyphen positional, non-UTF8 OsString.
#      FIRST documented Rust CLI library claiming pedantic POSIX
#      conformance.
#
#   4. NO META-FEATURES — Every other documented Rust CLI library
#      auto-generates SOMETHING (help, version, completion,
#      subcommand dispatch, color, env-fallback).  lexopt
#      DELIBERATELY OMITS all of these — they're user responsibility.
#      Compare R533 Logtalk's POSIX getopts (same philosophy in a
#      different ecosystem).  FIRST documented Rust CLI library
#      with zero auto-generated meta-features.
#
#   5. STREAMING-CONSUMER STATE MACHINE — lexopt's iterator design
#      lets the parser schema EVOLVE during parsing.  Order-
#      dependent flags, multi-value flags, subcommand-changes-
#      schema patterns all work naturally because parser state is
#      explicit in the user's loop.  Every other documented Rust
#      CLI library requires schema fixed at compile time.  FIRST
#      documented Rust CLI library with runtime-evolving schema.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/robertknight/ocrs/blob/main/ocrs-cli/src/main.rs
# `parse_args()` function and hand-rolled `--help` string literal.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '--help[print help and exit]' \
    '--version[print version and exit]' \
    '--allowed-chars=[filter characters produced by text recognition]:chars:' \
    '(-a --alphabet)'{-a+,--alphabet=}'[specify alphabet used by the recognition model]:chars:' \
    '--beam[use beam search for sequence decoding]' \
    '(-c --clipboard)'{-c,--clipboard}'[read input image from the system clipboard]' \
    '--debug[enable debug logging]' \
    '--detect-model=[use a custom text-detection model]:file:_files' \
    '(-j --json)'{-j,--json}'[output text and structure in JSON format]' \
    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[output file path (defaults to stdout)]:file:_files' \
    '(-p --png)'{-p,--png}'[output annotated copy of input image in PNG format]' \
    '--rec-model=[use a custom text-recognition model]:file:_files' \
    '--text-line-images[export images of identified text lines]' \
    '--text-map[generate a text-probability map for the input image]' \
    '--text-mask[generate a binary text-mask for the input image]' \
    '*:input image:_files -g "*.(png|PNG|jpg|JPG|jpeg|JPEG|webp|WEBP|tiff|TIFF|bmp|BMP)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
